# Sequence 04 — Tenant cloud federation (customer-cloud-broker)

The technical journey that wires a customer tenant into FORA. The customer stands up an OIDC trust between their IdP and FORA's customer-cloud-broker; the broker exchanges the trust for short-lived AWS / Azure / GCP credentials. Every assume is per-tenant, per-service, per-run, and bounded by a token bucket + circuit breaker.

## Diagram

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    actor Admin as Tenant cloud admin
    participant IdP as Tenant IdP (OIDC)
    participant CCB as Customer Cloud Broker
    participant Agent as Agent Runtime
    participant AWS as AWS APIs
    participant Probe as Probe Scheduler (5 min)
    participant Bus as NATS + event-bus-bridge
    participant Audit as Audit Account (SQS + S3)

    Note over Admin,CCB: One-time onboarding: tenant creates an OIDC IdP in their cloud,<br/>records the issuer URL + audience, and grants a role with a trust policy<br/>that pins to FORA's broker OIDC issuer.

    Admin->>CCB: POST /v1/tenants/acme-corp/cloud/config {provider:aws, role_arn, oidc_issuer, audience}
    CCB->>CCB: validate role trust policy (probe with a probe JWT)
    Probe->>CCB: probe (every 5 min)
    CCB->>AWS: sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity (probe JWT, scope=probe)
    AWS-->>CCB: scoped credentials
    CCB->>AWS: sts:GetCallerIdentity (verifies creds work)
    CCB->>AWS: sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity (release)
    CCB-->>Probe: ok
    Probe->>Audit: cloud.probe.ok {tenant=acme-corp, provider=aws}
    Note right of CCB: Probe uses a JWT signed by ProbeProbeSigner (ES256, scope=probe, 60s TTL).<br/>The real assume path refuses scope=probe JWTs.

    Agent->>CCB: POST /v1/tenants/acme-corp/cloud/assume {provider:aws, role_arn=acme-deploy, duration_sec=900, session_tags}
    CCB->>CCB: tenant+service token bucket check
    CCB->>CCB: circuit breaker state check
    CCB->>IdP: validate OIDC token (tenant's IdP)
    IdP-->>CCB: ok (subject=agent:developer, tenant=acme-corp)
    CCB->>AWS: sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity (forge-runtime JWT, aud=forge-runtime)
    AWS-->>CCB: short-lived credentials (15 min)
    CCB-->>Agent: {access_key, secret_key, session_token, expiry, handle_id}
    CCB->>Audit: cloud.assume {tenant=acme-corp, role=acme-deploy, handle_id, expiry}

    Agent->>AWS: s3:GetObject (using scoped creds)
    AWS-->>Agent: object
    Agent->>CCB: POST /v1/tenants/acme-corp/cloud/release {handle_id}
    CCB->>Audit: cloud.release {handle_id}
    Note over Agent,CCB: Release is idempotent. If the agent crashes mid-call, the broker's TTL<br/>on the handle reclaims the credentials at expiry.

    Note over CCB,Probe: If the probe fails for 3 consecutive ticks (15 min), the circuit breaker opens for the (tenant, provider) pair and subsequent assume calls return CIRCUIT_OPEN. The runbook is the only acceptable response.
```

## Notes

- **Per-tenant, per-service isolation.** The `acme-deploy` role is for AWS; `acme-terraform` is a separate role for a separate service. The token bucket is keyed on `(tenant, service)`, not on the agent name.
- **Canary probe with `scope=probe` JWT.** The probe JWT is refused by the real `assume` path; the role's trust policy explicitly denies the probe `aud`. Defence in depth.
- **Handle TTL.** Every assume returns a `handle_id` with a 15 min TTL. The release is best-effort; the broker reclaims the handle at expiry via a sweeper.
- **Session tags** (`session_tags` in the request) propagate to AWS as `sts:Tags`. The agent's `run_id`, `tenant_id`, and `agent_name` are stamped on the credential; the customer's CloudTrail shows the run that used the credential.
- **Deny-list** lives in the broker (per `mcp_server_configs.deny_list`). A denied role / action is refused at the broker; the call never reaches AWS.
- **The customer never shares a long-lived secret with FORA.** The trust is OIDC; the customer can revoke the trust at any time and FORA's next assume fails.
</file>

